  </header>

  <div class="bg-light-025 p6 bar-lg">
    <p class="fs-h3 fw-500 fc-dark mb4">
      Created in <strong>2019</strong> and now <strong>open source</strong>, Foundation CSS was born
      from a simple frustration: existing CSS frameworks were either too heavy, too opinionated, or
      not flexible enough.
    </p>

    <p class="fc-light-700 lh-relaxed">
      Inspired by
      <a
        href="https://stackoverflow.design/product/develop/using-stacks/"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener"
        class="fc-blue h:underline"
        >Stacks</a
      >
      and
      <a href="https://www.bbc.com/gel" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="fc-blue h:underline"
        >BBC GEL guidelines</a
      >, Foundation CSS follows atomic design principles where every class is an independent,
      composable building block.
    </p>

    <p class="fc-light-700 lh-relaxed">
      Our goal is to help you create <strong>beautiful, readable interfaces quickly</strong> that
      adapt correctly to all devices and are accessible to all people. Whether you're building a
      simple website or a complex web application, Foundation CSS provides the foundation for
      consistent, scalable design systems.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="d-flex fd-column g4">
  <header class="d-flex ai-center jc-space-between">
    <h2 id="atomic-vs-components">Atomic CSS vs Components</h2>
    <a href="#atomic-vs-components">üîó</a>
  </header>

  <div class="d-flex fd-column g4">
    <p class="fc-light-700 lh-relaxed">
      Foundation CSS excels at rapid prototyping and one-off styling, but it doesn't prevent you
      from creating traditional CSS components for repeated elements. Here's when to use each
      approach:
    </p>

    <div class="d-grid grid__1 md:grid__2 g6">
      <div class="d-flex fd-column g3 p4 bg-green-025 bar-md">
        <h3 class="fs-h3 fw-bold fc-green">‚úÖ Use Atomic Classes</h3>
        <ul class="list-unstyled fc-light-700">
          <li class="mb2">‚Ä¢ Quick prototypes and layouts</li>
          <li class="mb2">‚Ä¢ One-off styling needs</li>
          <li class="mb2">‚Ä¢ Responsive adjustments</li>
          <li class="mb2">‚Ä¢ Spacing and typography</li>
          <li class="mb2">‚Ä¢ Utility styling (colors, borders, etc.)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="d-flex fd-column g3 p4 bg-blue-025 bar-md">
        <h3 class="fs-h3 fw-bold fc-blue">üèóÔ∏è Create Components</h3>
        <ul class="list-unstyled fc-light-700">
          <li class="mb2">‚Ä¢ Repeated UI elements (buttons, cards, forms)</li>
          <li class="mb2">‚Ä¢ Complex interactions and animations</li>
          <li class="mb2">‚Ä¢ When atomic classes become too verbose</li>
          <li class="mb2">‚Ä¢ Brand-specific styling</li>
          <li class="mb2">‚Ä¢ Performance-critical components</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <aside class="bg-light-025 p4 bar-md">
      <h4 class="fs-h4 fw-bold mb3">üí° Pro Tip: Performance Optimization</h4>
      <p class="fc-light-700 mb3">
        Always arbitrate between atomic classes and components based on what will be lighter in
        terms of bundle size. When writing CSS, try to write it at the component level to avoid
        loading unnecessary CSS everywhere (unless the component is present on all pages).
      </p>

      <pre><code>// ‚ùå Too verbose - consider a component
&lt;button class="d-inline-flex ai-center jc-center bg-blue fc-white
               p3 bar-sm fw-500 t h:bg-blue-600 f:bg-blue-700"&gt;
  Submit
&lt;/button&gt;

// ‚úÖ Better as a component
&lt;button class="btn btn--primary"&gt;Submit&lt;/button&gt;</code></pre>
    </aside>
  </div>
</section>

